<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-701-088  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 701 088.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  July 1990 v22 n7 p21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A matter of definitions. (portable computer ) (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Seybold, Andrew.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users who want a portable computer must buy one where theoff-the-shelf model is close to what the user wants becauseadd-ins and add-ons are limited and it is hard to personalize aportable computer.andP;  Portable computers are classified as:transportable, units powered by AC power only regardless of sizeand weight that provide nearly equal desktop functions in aself-contained computer that can be moved; laptop computers,computers that use a combination of AC and battery power; notebookcomputers, computers that weigh under 5 pounds and run onbatteries; pocket computers, that do not have a full size keyboardand the mass storage devices are not industry standard; palmtopcomputers; and self-contained remote computers, includingcomputers already classified that have as an integral partcellular radios or transmitters and receivers so they can be usedin remote operations without wires.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Portable ComputersLaptop ComputersTerminologyDefinitionsTutorialHardware SelectionGuidelines.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Portable computer market segments. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>